    "note": "Measured on a shared x86-64 Linux cloud container (karac rebuilt from current kara main 056c08e), NOT the corpus's Apple M5 Pro. This kata has NO M5 results.json yet \u2014 it will be re-benched on the M5 and the canonical results.json added then; this file is the container reference run only. Absolute times/sizes/RSS are container numbers \u2014 not comparable to sibling katas' M5 tables; only within-file cross-language ratios are the signal. FAIRNESS (the headline, same discipline as #72): the kata builds the matrix as a Vec-of-Vec via Vec.new()+push (a GROWING dynamic array of GROWING rows), so every mirror builds it the same way \u2014 Rust Vec<Vec<i64>>::push, Go [][]int64 append, C a realloc-doubling vector of realloc-doubling rows, Python list-of-lists append \u2014 NOT a fixed 2-D array (which would be an apples-to-oranges heap-vs-stack comparison). The run is therefore allocation-dominated and measures growing-dynamic-array throughput. At equal semantics kara is the FASTEST of the four: kara 450.1ms < c 716.3ms (realloc) < rust 805.6ms (Vec::push) < go 1053.3ms (append). Single-threaded: the loop-carried hash is not a reduction the auto-par pass can split, so default `karac build` stays serial (verified equal to KARAC_AUTO_PAR=0, 450 vs 467ms, User\u2248wall) \u2014 a fair seq-vs-seq comparison. All five mirrors agree on the sink 222485272; the kata itself verifies byte-identical under karac run (JIT) / run --interp (tree-walk) / build (AOT) / KARAC_AUTO_PAR=0 build / Python across all ten correctness cases."
